ew ethnography and feminist scholarship. From this new perspective, Cole proposes an important critique of the dominant paradigm of southern European gender relations as being embedded in the code of honor and shame. Covering the Salazar years, as well as the period since the 1974 Revolution, Cole shows that fisherwomen of the past enjoyed greater autonomy in work and social relations than do their daughters and granddaughters, who live in a context of increasing commoditization and industrialization. Central to this account is an examination of the changing structure and role of the household as economic production moved to the factory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWomen fish trade workerszPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)vCase studies. 0aWomen fish trade workerszPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)vCase studies. 0aWomen fisherszPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)vCase studies. 0aWomen fisherszPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)vCase studies. 0aWomenzPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)xEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)xSocial conditions. 0aWomenzPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)xEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzPortugalzVila Chã (Porto)xSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aCatholic church.  aMatosinhos.  aNadel-Klein, Jane.  aOng, Aihwa.  aPorto.  aRogers, Susan.  aStavenhagen, Rodolfo.  aVila do Conde.  aVirgin Mary.  aanticlericalism.  abirth control.  achildbirth.  acourtship.  adeath.  adivorce.  aemigration.  aevil eye.  afestas.  afish selling.  agender role socialization.  aillegitimacy.  ainheritance.  ainveja.  alife stories.  amarriage.  apromessas.  arespeito.  aseaweed.  atourism.  atrabalhadeiras.  auxorilocal residence.  auxorivicinality.  awomen and factory work.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dD